{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012CAtFnyha4Fuby8L6q2SyM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→stepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n     3→inputDocuments:\n     4→  - _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/tech-spec-rust-stack-support.md\n     5→  - _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-operational-excellence.md\n     6→  - _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-operational-excellence.md\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→# Rust Stack Support - Epic Breakdown\n    10→\n    11→## Overview\n    12→\n    13→This document provides the complete epic and story breakdown for adding full Rust stack support to codeharness at parity with Node.js and Python.\n    14→\n    15→## Requirements Inventory\n    16→\n    17→### Functional Requirements\n    18→\n    19→FR1: System detects Rust projects via `Cargo.toml` presence and returns stack `'rust'`\n    20→FR2: System detects Rust app type (CLI, server, library, agent, generic) by parsing `Cargo.toml` sections and dependencies\n    21→FR3: System detects `[workspace]` projects and treats them as single projects with `--workspace` flags\n    22→FR4: System generates multi-stage Dockerfile for Rust projects (build + runtime stages)\n    23→FR5: System installs OTLP crates (`opentelemetry`, `opentelemetry-otlp`, `tracing-opentelemetry`, `tracing-subscriber`) via `cargo add`\n    24→FR6: System provides LLM guidance doc for Rust OTLP instrumentation (`templates/otlp/rust.md`)\n    25→FR7: System detects `cargo-tarpaulin` as coverage tool for Rust projects\n    26→FR8: System parses `tarpaulin-report.json` for coverage percentage\n    27→FR9: System parses `cargo test` output for pass/fail counts\n    28→FR10: System generates AGENTS.md with Rust build/test commands\n    29→FR11: System creates Semgrep rules for Rust observability patterns (`tracing` crate)\n    30→FR12: System creates verification Dockerfile for Rust projects\n    31→FR13: System registers `cargo-tarpaulin` in dependency registry\n    32→FR14: System expands state types to support Rust coverage tool and OTLP config\n    33→\n    34→### NonFunctional Requirements\n    35→\n    36→NFR1: No file exceeds 300 lines (existing constraint from architecture)\n    37→NFR2: All new code has unit tests — 0 regressions on existing tests\n    38→NFR3: No new npm dependencies added to codeharness itself\n    39→NFR4: Cargo.toml parsing uses simple string matching — no TOML parser dependency\n    40→NFR5: All changes follow existing Result<T> pattern and module boundaries\n    41→\n    42→### Additional Requirements\n    43→\n    44→- Workspace detection must not break single-crate projects (false positive guard)\n    45→- `cargo-tarpaulin` is runtime-only dependency — not required at codeharness build time\n    46→- Semgrep Rust rules target standard `tracing` crate patterns only (custom macros out of scope)\n    47→- Verification Dockerfile needs Python for Semgrep even in Rust projects\n    48→\n    49→### FR Coverage Map\n    50→\n    51→| FR | Epic | Story |\n    52→|----|------|-------|\n    53→| FR1, FR2, FR3 | Epic 1 | 8-1 |\n    54→| FR14 | Epic 1 | 8-2 |\n    55→| FR7, FR8, FR9 | Epic 2 | 8-3 |\n    56→| FR13 | Epic 2 | 8-4 |\n    57→| FR4 | Epic 3 | 8-5 |\n    58→| FR12 | Epic 3 | 8-6 |\n    59→| FR5, FR6 | Epic 4 | 8-7 |\n    60→| FR10 | Epic 4 | 8-8 |\n    61→| FR11 | Epic 5 | 8-9 |\n    62→\n    63→## Epic List\n    64→\n    65→- **Epic 1: Rust Detection Foundation** — Stack detection, app type detection, state type expansion\n    66→- **Epic 2: Rust Coverage & Testing** — cargo-tarpaulin detection, report parsing, test output parsing\n    67→- **Epic 3: Rust Infrastructure** — Dockerfile template, verification Dockerfile\n    68→- **Epic 4: Rust Observability & Docs** — OTLP instrumentation, guidance doc, docs scaffolding\n    69→- **Epic 5: Rust Static Analysis** — Semgrep rules for tracing patterns\n    70→\n    71→## Epic 1: Rust Detection Foundation\n    72→\n    73→Enable codeharness to recognize Rust projects, detect their type, and store Rust-specific state.\n    74→\n    75→### Story 8-1: Rust stack and app type detection\n    76→\n    77→As a developer initializing codeharness on a Rust project,\n    78→I want the harness to detect my project as Rust and identify whether it's a CLI, server, library, or agent,\n    79→So that all downstream features (coverage, OTLP, Dockerfile) use the correct Rust configuration.\n    80→\n    81→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    82→\n    83→**Given** a directory contains `Cargo.toml`\n    84→**When** `detectStack()` is called\n    85→**Then** it returns `'rust'`\n    86→\n    87→**Given** a Rust project with `[[bin]]` in Cargo.toml and no web framework deps\n    88→**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n    89→**Then** it returns `'cli'`\n    90→\n    91→**Given** a Rust project with `axum` in `[dependencies]`\n    92→**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n    93→**Then** it returns `'server'`\n    94→\n    95→**Given** a Rust project with `[lib]` section and no `[[bin]]`\n    96→**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n    97→**Then** it returns `'generic'` (library)\n    98→\n    99→**Given** a Rust project with `async-openai` in dependencies\n   100→**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n   101→**Then** it returns `'agent'`\n   102→\n   103→**Given** a Rust project with `[workspace]` in Cargo.toml\n   104→**When** `detectStack()` is called\n   105→**Then** it still returns `'rust'` (treated as single project)\n   106→\n   107→**Given** no `Cargo.toml` exists\n   108→**When** `detectStack()` is called\n   109→**Then** Rust is NOT detected (no false positive)\n   110→\n   111→### Story 8-2: Expand state types for Rust\n   112→\n   113→As a developer,\n   114→I want the harness state to support Rust-specific fields,\n   115→So that coverage tool and OTLP config are correctly stored.\n   116→\n   117→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   118→\n   119→**Given** a Rust project is initialized\n   120→**When** state is written\n   121→**Then** `coverage.tool` accepts `'cargo-tarpaulin'` without type errors\n   122→\n   123→**Given** a Rust project has OTLP configured\n   124→**When** state is written\n   125→**Then** `otlp.rust_env_hint` field is present with value `'OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT'`\n   126→\n   127→## Epic 2: Rust Coverage & Testing\n   128→\n   129→Enable coverage detection, report parsing, and test output parsing for Rust projects using cargo-tarpaulin.\n   130→\n   131→### Story 8-3: cargo-tarpaulin coverage detection and parsing\n   132→\n   133→As a developer running coverage on a Rust project,\n   134→I want codeharness to detect cargo-tarpaulin, run it, and parse the JSON report,\n   135→So that coverage metrics are tracked at parity with Node.js/Python.\n   136→\n   137→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   138→\n   139→**Given** a Rust project with `cargo-tarpaulin` installed\n   140→**When** `detectCoverageTool()` is called\n   141→**Then** it returns `{ tool: 'cargo-tarpaulin', runCommand: 'cargo tarpaulin --out json --output-dir coverage/', reportFormat: 'tarpaulin-json' }`\n   142→\n   143→**Given** a Rust workspace project\n   144→**When** `detectCoverageTool()` is called\n   145→**Then** the run command includes `--workspace` flag\n   146→\n   147→**Given** a `coverage/tarpaulin-report.json` file with `\"coverage\": 85.5`\n   148→**When** `parseCoverageReport()` is called with format `'tarpaulin-json'`\n   149→**Then** it returns `85.5`\n   150→\n   151→**Given** `cargo test` output containing `test result: ok. 42 passed; 3 failed; 0 ignored`\n   152→**When** `parseTestCounts()` is called\n   153→**Then** it returns `{ passCount: 42, failCount: 3 }`\n   154→\n   155→**Given** `cargo-tarpaulin` is NOT installed\n   156→**When** `detectCoverageTool()` is called on a Rust project\n   157→**Then** it returns `{ tool: 'unknown' }` with a warning\n   158→\n   159→### Story 8-4: Register cargo-tarpaulin in dependency registry\n   160→\n   161→As a developer initializing codeharness on a Rust project,\n   162→I want cargo-tarpaulin to be auto-installed if missing,\n   163→So that coverage works out of the box.\n   164→\n   165→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   166→\n   167→**Given** `cargo-tarpaulin` is not installed\n   168→**When** `codeharness init` runs on a Rust project\n   169→**Then** it attempts `cargo install cargo-tarpaulin`\n   170→\n   171→**Given** the dependency registry\n   172→**When** checked for `cargo-tarpaulin`\n   173→**Then** it has `critical: false`, install command `cargo install cargo-tarpaulin`, check command `cargo tarpaulin --version`\n   174→\n   175→## Epic 3: Rust Infrastructure\n   176→\n   177→Generate Dockerfiles for Rust project deployment and verification.\n   178→\n   179→### Story 8-5: Rust Dockerfile template generation\n   180→\n   181→As a developer deploying a Rust project,\n   182→I want codeharness to generate a multi-stage Dockerfile,\n   183→So that I get a minimal runtime image with just the compiled binary.\n   184→\n   185→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   186→\n   187→**Given** a Rust project without a Dockerfile\n   188→**When** `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called\n   189→**Then** it writes a multi-stage Dockerfile with `rust:1.82-slim` builder and `debian:bookworm-slim` runtime\n   190→\n   191→**Given** the generated Dockerfile\n   192→**When** inspected\n   193→**Then** it includes `cargo build --release` in build stage, `curl`/`jq` in runtime stage, and runs as non-root user\n   194→\n   195→**Given** a Rust project with an existing Dockerfile\n   196→**When** `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called\n   197→**Then** it returns `fail('Dockerfile already exists')`\n   198→\n   199→### Story 8-6: Rust verification Dockerfile\n   200→\n   201→As a developer verifying a Rust project,\n   202→I want a verification environment with Rust tooling, Semgrep, and showboat,\n   203→So that automated verification works for Rust projects.\n   204→\n   205→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   206→\n   207→**Given** `templates/Dockerfile.verify.rust` exists\n   208→**When** built\n   209→**Then** it includes `rust:1.82-slim`, Python + Semgrep, showboat, cargo-tarpaulin, curl, jq\n   210→\n   211→**Given** the verification Dockerfile\n   212→**When** inspected\n   213→**Then** OTLP environment variables are configured pointing to host Docker endpoint\n   214→\n   215→## Epic 4: Rust Observability & Documentation\n   216→\n   217→Add OTLP instrumentation support and documentation scaffolding for Rust projects.\n   218→\n   219→### Story 8-7: Rust OTLP instrumentation\n   220→\n   221→As a developer instrumenting a Rust project,\n   222→I want codeharness to add OpenTelemetry crates and provide setup guidance,\n   223→So that I can quickly enable observability.\n   224→\n   225→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   226→\n   227→**Given** a Rust project\n   228→**When** `instrumentProject()` runs\n   229→**Then** `cargo add opentelemetry opentelemetry-otlp tracing-opentelemetry tracing-subscriber` is executed\n   230→\n   231→**Given** OTLP instrumentation succeeds\n   232→**When** state is updated\n   233→**Then** `configureOtlpEnvVars()` writes `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` and `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME` to `.env.codeharness`\n   234→\n   235→**Given** a Rust project\n   236→**When** `configureAgent()` is called\n   237→**Then** it skips with info message (no standard Rust agent SDK yet)\n   238→\n   239→**Given** `templates/otlp/rust.md` exists\n   240→**When** read\n   241→**Then** it contains: packages to add, `tracing_subscriber` setup code snippet, `#[tracing::instrument]` usage, env vars, verification steps\n   242→\n   243→### Story 8-8: Rust documentation scaffolding\n   244→\n   245→As a developer initializing a Rust project,\n   246→I want AGENTS.md to include Rust-specific build/test commands,\n   247→So that AI agents know how to build and test my project.\n   248→\n   249→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   250→\n   251→**Given** a Rust project\n   252→**When** `getStackLabel()` is called\n   253→**Then** it returns `'Rust (Cargo.toml)'`\n   254→\n   255→**Given** a Rust project\n   256→**When** `getCoverageTool()` is called\n   257→**Then** it returns `'cargo-tarpaulin'`\n   258→\n   259→**Given** a Rust project\n   260→**When** `generateAgentsMdContent()` is called\n   261→**Then** output includes `cargo build`, `cargo test`, `cargo tarpaulin --out json`\n   262→\n   263→**Given** a Rust project with `[package] name = \"myapp\"` in Cargo.toml\n   264→**When** `getProjectName()` is called\n   265→**Then** it returns `'myapp'` (reads from Cargo.toml, not package.json)\n   266→\n   267→## Epic 5: Rust Static Analysis\n   268→\n   269→Create Semgrep rules to detect observability gaps in Rust code using tracing crate patterns.\n   270→\n   271→### Story 8-9: Semgrep rules for Rust observability\n   272→\n   273→As a developer auditing a Rust project,\n   274→I want Semgrep to detect functions and error paths without tracing,\n   275→So that observability gaps are identified automatically.\n   276→\n   277→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   278→\n   279→**Given** a Rust function without `tracing::debug!`, `tracing::info!`, or `#[instrument]`\n   280→**When** Semgrep runs with `rust-function-no-tracing` rule\n   281→**Then** it reports an observability gap\n   282→\n   283→**Given** a Rust `match` arm handling `Err` without `tracing::error!` or `tracing::warn!`\n   284→**When** Semgrep runs with `rust-catch-without-tracing` rule\n   285→**Then** it reports an observability gap\n   286→\n   287→**Given** a Rust `.map_err()` or `.unwrap_or_else()` closure without tracing macros\n   288→**When** Semgrep runs with `rust-error-path-no-tracing` rule\n   289→**Then** it reports an observability gap\n   290→\n   291→**Given** all 3 Rust rule files in `patches/observability/`\n   292→**When** `codeharness audit` runs on a Rust project with Semgrep installed\n   293→**Then** the observability static analysis dimension uses the Rust rules automatically (Semgrep auto-discovers by `languages: [rust]`)\n   294→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01L8FFCpVh7KBCcfMN3fKhC4","session_id":"900ad046-8ed4-4678-b2b2-9fd66fbde286","uuid":"2b5ede6b-ae66-4a2c-8045-8283ba157cf9","timestamp":"2026-03-23T05:51:37.689Z"}
