{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LyWdFekkE8vACbwEv6NGNX","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Summary\n\nImplemented all 5 tasks for story 8-3 (cargo-tarpaulin coverage detection and parsing).\n\n**Files modified:**\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/coverage.ts` -- replaced the rust stub in `detectCoverageTool()` with tarpaulin install check via `execSync`, workspace detection via `[workspace]` regex on `Cargo.toml`, correct `--output-dir coverage/` flag; added `parseTarpaulinCoverage()` function; wired `tarpaulin-json` into `parseCoverageReport()`; added cargo test regex to `parseTestCounts()`.\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/__tests__/coverage.test.ts` -- added 11 new tests covering all 5 ACs: tarpaulin installed detection (AC1), workspace flag (AC2), tarpaulin report parsing with valid/missing/malformed/empty-field cases (AC3), cargo test output parsing for ok/FAILED/all-passed formats (AC4), tarpaulin-not-installed fallback (AC5). Used `vi.mock('node:child_process')` with `importOriginal` for ESM-compatible mocking.\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/8-3-cargo-tarpaulin-coverage-detection.md` -- marked all ACs and tasks complete, status set to `review`.\n\n**Test results:** 2979 tests passed, 0 failed, 0 regressions.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **ESM mocking limitation:** `vi.spyOn` cannot spy on `execSync` from `node:child_process` in ESM mode. Workaround: used `vi.mock('node:child_process', async (importOriginal) => ...)` to create a mockable wrapper while preserving real implementations for non-mocked calls. This is the standard vitest pattern but adds a file-level mock that applies to all tests in the file (mitigated by `mockReset()` in `afterEach`).\n- **Cargo test regex ordering:** The cargo test regex (`test result:.*?(\\d+) passed; (\\d+) failed`) was placed before the pytest regex (`(\\d+) passed, (\\d+) failed`) because the pytest regex would false-match on cargo test output that contains \"N passed\" strings. The ordering matters and is correct, but a future contributor could reorder and break cargo test parsing.\n- **No integration test for actual `cargo tarpaulin` execution:** All tests mock the subprocess call. There is no integration test that actually runs `cargo tarpaulin` on a real Rust project, since the CI environment may not have Rust/tarpaulin installed. This is consistent with how Node.js and Python coverage tool tests work in this codebase."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a0b46b1d19bdea0d8 (use SendMessage with to: 'a0b46b1d19bdea0d8' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 63736\ntool_uses: 57\nduration_ms: 351330</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"900ad046-8ed4-4678-b2b2-9fd66fbde286","uuid":"37dcd9bd-9227-49e2-a880-9f37a68ee538","timestamp":"2026-03-23T06:01:11.822Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-dev-story for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/8-3-cargo-tarpaulin-coverage-detection.md — implement all tasks, write tests, and mark the story for review. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously through all tasks until complete. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (build failures, test failures, unclear task specs, missing APIs)\n- Workarounds applied (anything hacky, copied patterns that felt wrong, TODOs left behind)\n- Code quality concerns (areas that need refactoring, edge cases not handled, tech debt added)\n- Observations (unexpected complexity, architectural mismatches, dependency issues)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a0b46b1d19bdea0d8","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Summary\n\nImplemented all 5 tasks for story 8-3 (cargo-tarpaulin coverage detection and parsing).\n\n**Files modified:**\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/coverage.ts` -- replaced the rust stub in `detectCoverageTool()` with tarpaulin install check via `execSync`, workspace detection via `[workspace]` regex on `Cargo.toml`, correct `--output-dir coverage/` flag; added `parseTarpaulinCoverage()` function; wired `tarpaulin-json` into `parseCoverageReport()`; added cargo test regex to `parseTestCounts()`.\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/__tests__/coverage.test.ts` -- added 11 new tests covering all 5 ACs: tarpaulin installed detection (AC1), workspace flag (AC2), tarpaulin report parsing with valid/missing/malformed/empty-field cases (AC3), cargo test output parsing for ok/FAILED/all-passed formats (AC4), tarpaulin-not-installed fallback (AC5). Used `vi.mock('node:child_process')` with `importOriginal` for ESM-compatible mocking.\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/8-3-cargo-tarpaulin-coverage-detection.md` -- marked all ACs and tasks complete, status set to `review`.\n\n**Test results:** 2979 tests passed, 0 failed, 0 regressions.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **ESM mocking limitation:** `vi.spyOn` cannot spy on `execSync` from `node:child_process` in ESM mode. Workaround: used `vi.mock('node:child_process', async (importOriginal) => ...)` to create a mockable wrapper while preserving real implementations for non-mocked calls. This is the standard vitest pattern but adds a file-level mock that applies to all tests in the file (mitigated by `mockReset()` in `afterEach`).\n- **Cargo test regex ordering:** The cargo test regex (`test result:.*?(\\d+) passed; (\\d+) failed`) was placed before the pytest regex (`(\\d+) passed, (\\d+) failed`) because the pytest regex would false-match on cargo test output that contains \"N passed\" strings. The ordering matters and is correct, but a future contributor could reorder and break cargo test parsing.\n- **No integration test for actual `cargo tarpaulin` execution:** All tests mock the subprocess call. There is no integration test that actually runs `cargo tarpaulin` on a real Rust project, since the CI environment may not have Rust/tarpaulin installed. This is consistent with how Node.js and Python coverage tool tests work in this codebase."}],"totalDurationMs":351330,"totalTokens":63736,"totalToolUseCount":57,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":481,"cache_read_input_tokens":62565,"output_tokens":689,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":481},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
