{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FMDkUeUKeSEdVYnaeX8sCM","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\n\n**Review complete.** Here is what was done:\n\n**Files modified:**\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/coverage.ts` — Fixed `parseTestCounts()` to aggregate multiple `test result:` lines from workspace cargo test output (was only capturing first crate)\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/__tests__/coverage.test.ts` — Added workspace aggregation test (68 tests total, 2980 suite-wide)\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/AGENTS.md` — Updated coverage.ts description to mention cargo-tarpaulin\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/8-3-cargo-tarpaulin-coverage-detection.md` — Status changed to `verifying`, review notes appended\n\n**Coverage results:** `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` passes — all 123 files above 80% per-file floor, overall 97% (above 90% target).\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found and fixed:**\n- **HIGH**: `parseTestCounts()` only captured first `test result:` line from cargo test output. Workspace projects emit one per crate, so counts were wrong. Fixed with global regex + aggregation loop.\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW):**\n- No type validation on `parseTarpaulinCoverage` — if tarpaulin report has `\"coverage\": \"85.5\"` (string), `?? 0` won't catch it. Low risk since tarpaulin always outputs a number.\n- `checkOnlyCoverage()` calls `detectCoverageTool()` which shells out to `cargo tarpaulin --version` for Rust projects — unnecessary side effect in check-only mode. Pre-existing pattern, not introduced by this story.\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n- `src/lib/coverage.ts` branch coverage is 77.98% — below 80% floor for branches, but this is caused by pre-existing untested branches (lines 108-209, 234-272 in `runCoverage` and Node/Python detection paths), not by the new Rust code. The per-file check uses statement coverage (90.51%) which passes.\n- No integration test for end-to-end Rust project coverage run (would require actual Rust toolchain).\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n- None. The implementation follows established patterns exactly (filesystem fixtures, vi.mock for subprocess, switch-based format dispatch).\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:**\n- None. All HIGH and MEDIUM issues fixed. Story moved to `verifying`."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a5d1c82f6480bcf68 (use SendMessage with to: 'a5d1c82f6480bcf68' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 63772\ntool_uses: 54\nduration_ms: 351339</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"900ad046-8ed4-4678-b2b2-9fd66fbde286","uuid":"bf5ba919-1a1e-42e1-8921-13777be633a0","timestamp":"2026-03-23T06:07:34.327Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/8-3-cargo-tarpaulin-coverage-detection.md — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Bugs found and their severity (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW with brief description)\n- Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt)\n- Coverage gaps (files below floor, untested edge cases, areas needing integration tests)\n- Architecture concerns (patterns that don't fit, coupling issues, missing abstractions)\n- Items sent back for re-development (what failed and why)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a5d1c82f6480bcf68","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\n\n**Re